Let's break this down in a very simple, real-world way. We'll use a **bakery **as a metaphor to explain Go modules, packages, imports, and the main package. 🔹 Imagine: You're running a bakery shop. Your shop has multiple departments: Bread, Cakes, Billing, etc. Each department has its own set of tools and recipes (code). You also sell your baked goods to customers (this is your main service). 📦 1. What is a Go package? A package is like a department in your bakery: bread → All code to make bread. cake → All code to make cakes. billing → All code to handle payments. Each department (package) focuses on a specific job and has its own folder. // cake/cake.go package cake
func MakeCake() string { return "Chocolate Cake" }
